The contributor is not sure about the analysis and neither am I. It looks more like 3⋅20 than like 4⋅20. Note that 60 is composed of a complex addition of numerals instead, as one might expect, of 3⋅20. Perhaps what we see here is the old numeral for 60 that is now used for 80. This might be interpreted as a sign of erosion of the original numeral system.
Could also include 1⋅ (na-) but based on 200 this rather is a part of '100' itself (though more data would be needed to be sure).
